RECORDED BY MISS S. E. WALDO (A DISCIPLE) MONDAY, June 24, 1895. (The reading today was from the Bhakti-Sutras by Nārada.)
&ldquo;Extreme love to God is Bhakti, and this love is the real immortality, getting which a man becomes perfectly satisfied, sorrows for no loss, and is never jealous; knowing which man becomes mad.&rdquo;
My Master used to say, &ldquo;This world is a huge lunatic asylum where all men are mad, some after money, some after women, some after name or fame, and a few after God.

RECORDED BY MISS S. E. WALDO (A DISCIPLE) FRIDAY, July 12, 1895. (Shankara&rsquo;s Commentary.)
Fourth Vyasa Sutra. &ldquo;Âtman (is) the aim of all.&rdquo;
Ishvara is to be known from the Vedanta; all Vedas point to Him (Who is the Cause; the Creator, Preserver and Destroyer). Ishvara is the unification of the Trinity, known as Brahmā, Vishnu, and Shiva, which stand at the head of the Hindu Pantheon. &ldquo;Thou art our Father who takest us to the other shore of the dark ocean&rdquo; (Disciple&rsquo;s words to the Master).

RECORDED BY MISS S. E. WALDO (A DISCIPLE) SUNDAY, July 28, 1895. (Avadhuta Gita or &ldquo;Song of the Purified&rdquo; by Dattātreya (Dattatreya, the son of Atri and Anasuyā, was an incarnation of Brahmā, Vishnu and Shiva.))
&ldquo;All knowledge depends upon calmness of mind.&rdquo;
&ldquo;He who has filled the universe, He who is Self in self, how shall I salute Him!&rdquo;
To know the Atman as my nature is both knowledge and realisation.

RECORDED BY MISS S. E. WALDO (A DISCIPLE) SUNDAY, August 4, 1895.
&ldquo;Whom the ignorant worship, Him I preach unto thee.&rdquo;
This one and only God is the &ldquo;knownest&rdquo; of the known. He is the one thing we see everywhere. All know their own Self, all know, &ldquo;I am&rdquo;, even animals. All we know is the projection of the Self. Teach this to the children, they can grasp it. Every religion has worshipped the Self, even though unconsciously, because there is nothing else.
